One architecture change that saves you real money: drop Celery + Redis for now

This is the biggest cost trap in your current setup. A Celery worker needs an always-on process — nothing free stays always-on for a background worker (free tiers only cover request-driven web services, not idle daemons). Redis itself has a fine free tier (Upstash gives a real free allowance), but the worker process is the problem.

At zero-to-low traffic, you don't need a task queue yet. Replace process_session.delay(...) with FastAPI's built-in BackgroundTasks — it runs the same pipeline function, in-process, right after the HTTP response is sent, no separate worker or Redis required. Your workers/tasks.py logic barely changes; you're just calling the function directly instead of through Celery. This removes an entire piece of paid infrastructure until you actually have concurrent load that needs a real queue.

The one real cost: OpenAI usage

There's no meaningful free tier for Whisper/GPT-4o-mini — it's pay-as-you-go from the first API call. But per session it's pennies, so the move isn't "find it for free," it's make it uncapped-cost-impossible:

Hard per-user daily/weekly session limits (which you already want for the free-tier plan we discussed)
A global daily spend cap you check before letting a new session start — reject gracefully ("try again tomorrow") rather than silently letting costs run
Keep an eye on OpenAI's usage dashboard weekly while you're small

If you want to shave even that down, it's worth checking current pricing on Groq — they run Whisper-class transcription and small models very cheaply/quickly — but confirm current numbers yourself before switching, pricing in this space moves often.

What "free" actually costs you (be aware, not scared)
Cold starts: Render's free web service sleeps after inactivity and takes several seconds to wake up on the next request. Annoying for a demo link, fine for pre-launch.
Neon free tier storage/compute caps: fine for hundreds of users' worth of session data, not for scale — but you'll have revenue signal long before you hit it.
No real backups/PITR on most free DB tiers — export a manual pg_dump periodically so a free-tier hiccup can't lose your only user data.
When to start paying

The honest trigger isn't a date, it's a symptom: cold starts annoying real users, or you're bumping a free-tier storage/compute cap. At that point the upgrade path is additive, not a rebuild — swap Render free → Render paid or Neon free → Neon paid, add Celery+Redis back once you actually have concurrent processing load worth queuing. Nothing above locks you into a provider that makes migrating painful later.

